ook is an important study of how white North Americans saw first-wave South Asian immigrants as separate from, and inferior to, other groups in the evolving racial hierarchy on the west coast of North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantsxHealth and hygienezPacific Coast (North America)xHistoryy20th century. 0aMarginality, SocialzPacific Coast (North America)xHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthxPolitical aspectszPacific Coast (North America)xHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthxSocial aspectszPacific Coast (North America)xHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzPacific Coast (North America)xHistoryy20th century. 0aSouth AsiansxHealth and hygienezPacific Coast (North America)xHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311141793640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774832205423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774832205/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-141793-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles